Graphite powder, potassium permanganate (KMnO4), sodium nitrate (NaNO3), sulfuric acid (H2SO
                           4
                        ), hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), HAuCl4⋅3H2O (pro analysis grade), glutathione (GSH), uric acid (UA), tryptophan (Trp) and other reagents were purchased from Merck Company (Darmstadt, Germany). Phosphate buffer solution (PBS) 0.1M was prepared in the pH range of 2.0–11.0. Double distilled water was used for preparing all solutions.

To form a thin film of GQDs, the well-cleaned GCE was immersed into GQDs aqueous solution for 12h at room temperature to obtain a homogeneous GQDs/GCE. GQDs suspension (0.5mgmL−1) was prepared by dispersing GQDs in deionized water; following ultrasonication is used for 1h. Then, the GQDs/GCE electrode was electrochemically cycled between 0.0 and −1.4 V (vs. Ag/AgCl) for 15 cycles in PBS (pH=7) at a scan rate of 50mVs−1. By the reduction of oxygen functional groups such as epoxide, carboxyl, and hydroxyl present on the GQDs, ERGQDs/GCE was obtained (Fig. 1
                        ). Then the ERGQDs/GCE was immersed in to 0.1molL−1 KNO3 solution containing 1.0mM HAuCl4. AuNPs electrochemically deposited on the ERGQDs/GCE electrode under the constant potential of −0.2V (vs. SCE) for 40s to obtain Au/ERGQDs/GCE electrode. Afterwards, to improve electrocatalytic activity and charge injection, the Au/ERGQDs/GCE electrode was immersed in aqueous solution of 4-(((4-mercaptophenyl)imino)methyl) benzene-1,2-diol (1.0mM of MIB) for 4h, at room temperature. This electrode is termed as MIB/Au/ERGQDs/GCE electrode. Scheme 1
                         illustrates the schematic representation for the modification of GCE with ERGQDs, Au and MIB.

Differential pulse voltammetry (DPV) was used to determine the linear range and detection limit of GSH at MIB/Au/ERGQDs/GCE. The plot of peak vs. GSH concentration yielded two calibration plots corresponding to two concentration ranges of 0.03–40.0μM and 40.0–1300.0μM with slopes of 0.503 and 0.036 μA μM−
                        1 respectively (Fig. 10
                        ). The detection limit was obtained as 9nM using the calibration equation of first linear segment. The obtained results compared with values reported by other research groups (Table 1
                        ).
